snippet.textDisplay:
I may hate the cold weather and don't celebrate Christmas do to being Jewish, but I can still relate. I lived in Maine when I was a kid, also known as the second coldest state next to Alask, and it was the first place I ever saw snow over my ankles. I still hold good memories my friends and I building snow forts, having snow ball fights, and sledding down the hill behind our house. I was a amazing to see all the holiday cheer in the frosty bays of December, even when we got eight feet of snow in a day. Though I will say that I rather enjoy celebrating Hanukkah in Tennessee with my relatives, in 50 degree weather.

Thanks for the video it was fun. Keep up the good work.

snippet.textDisplay:
Gunna be a downer realist and say it might be because of that childhood nostalgia. I used to love winter when I was a child. I would wake up every first snowfall and run to wake up my parents and everyone so we could go playing in the snow. And snow days were the best. But as myself and my siblings got older and became adults that wonder.. simply vanished. Now winter is mostly about shoveling and heating up your car before you go to work so you don’t absolutely hate life. We always say, “If it only snowed Christmas week, that would be perfect.” And nod to ourselves because (living in Minnesota) that will never happen.
Though I got off track a bit. Your video did remind me of the reasons I used to love winter (and that many friends from other regions call me fortunate) and I shall try to look at it with childlike wonder once again.

snippet.textDisplay: I live in Germany and the last Years there hasnt been any Snow in the City where I live. I just miss it sometimes, waking up to the nearly untouched white neighbourhood, the sound when you walk through fresh snow, and when you later get home, the feeling of warming up slowly from the inside and eating soup or drinking hot chocolate. And for the last years we had pretty much Fall for like one half of the year and the rest would be all summer. Thanks to global warming i guess.

snippet.textDisplay: So, that wrapping paper thing... It's kinda fun once you get the hang of it. Make sure your scissors are clean and sharp or it won't go well. You build the skill/work up to it by pushing the scissors along the paper while executing a complete scissor motion. Once you get the hang of moving the scissors farther along than they would just by normal cutting, you just initiate the cut while pushing, then hold the scissor motion still while pushing evenly. Opening the scissors will halt the process, and inconsistent forward motion will mess up a nice, clean cut edge.
